Text.Value: No offence, but my first experience with your kind was one of your dragons nearly roasting me alive.
I... feel better too. Now that the voices are gone.
A relative safe haven, I suppose. I'll be here if you need me.
And even then, only for a moment. Until I got here.
You have a tadpole too. I'm the only one who lost her bloody mind.
You have nothing to fear from me, so long as the feeling's mutual.
I'll extend the grace you gave me and pretend that's not a threat.
You can stay here, in camp.
But I promise any future murderous intentions will be thoroughly justified.
The forgiving sort, are you?
Let's set off. Time is against us.
Beyond 'Shadowheart'? There's not much to say.
I'm sure you have questions.
Nothing. Just an inkling.
Yes. Let's get moving.
My kin fought the ghaik menace for generations. We know their ways.
I'm glad to run into a fellow half-elf.
I'm just glad to see you're feeling better.
Perhaps you'll learn more in time then. If we have time, that is.
Agreed. Do you have any ideas?
Leave.
You seem uncomfortable around my kind - why?
Leave.
Run. Run. Find her. It only ever stopped when I went the right direction.
Run. Run. Find him. It only ever stopped when I went the right direction.
Run. Run. Find them. It only ever stopped when I went the right direction.

EditorData.NodeContext: It's difficult to articulate. Like describing a fading dream upon waking,.

Text.Value: I won't refuse some company. So long as it's outside my head.
And what does your gith companion have to say about that?
I'm sure things will sort themselves out on the road.
Not still harbouring urges to kill me, are you?
I'm not much for bowing and scraping, but... thank you.
This is no laughing matter. I mightn't be so understanding in future.
Remarkably calm for a woman I planned to run through. I can appreciate that.
Remarkably calm for a man I planned to run through.  I can appreciate that.
Remarkably calm for someone I planned to run through.  I can appreciate that.
What's wrong with Lae'zel?
I doubt we'd make it in time. There has to be someone else nearby.
I'll do what I can. It was difficult to do... anything in that haze.
Even if that gith over there doesn't seem to like me.
A haunting pack of voices almost drove me to murder you, and my name is strange?
But no doubt there's a tadpole squirming in our heads. We have to act.
Indeed, our last talk was abrupt, let's say. Tell me about yourself.
These voices could be to do with our infection.
We're all in this together. Whatever the issue with her is... best if you forget it.
I'm not ruling anything out. Unfortunately that doesn't leave me with a lot of firm answers.
Turn to other matters.
And your fellow gith stares at me like she's contemplating how my heart tastes.
We need only find my kin. They will have a cure.
The voices wanted you to find me? Personally?
They do? I... well. That's curious.
My head's been in a fog for days. This morning, it cleared away.
Staying in this camp is making me... restless.
Tell me about these voices again. There must be more to them.
If the voices return, tell me at once.
Strange bedfellows and such. All right.
If you say so. Honestly, I feel fine. Better than ever, in ways.
You should be grateful. Not many outsiders ever benefit from githyanki knowledge.
Travel with me. I think we can both be of use to each other.
'We'? You tried to kill me, remember? I didn't agree to a partnership.
I'll save my gratitude for when I'm cured.
No. As long as the voices stay away, I think you're safe.
Apparently so. They weren't inclined to explain why, just to drive half-berserk.
I didn't mean... fine. Yes. If you have a cure, then I need it as much as you do.

EditorData.NodeContext: She'll go along with it for now.

Text.Value: Sounds like you'll keep things interesting, at least.
We're not exactly special. There's a lot of bored elves and curious humans out there.
Or perhaps I was mistaken, keeping your around.
And trust me, I'd love an explanation.
Shadowheart? Interesting. Would've pegged you for a 'Molly', myself.
But I don't want to stray far. I've already learned the consequences the hard way.
They weren't distinct. Just... this constant onslaught.

EditorData.NodeContext: It's difficult to articulate. Like describing a fading dream upon waking,.

Text.Value: You I don't mind, but your... kin is another story.
I was on my way to Baldur's Gate when that ship appeared. Considering our... shared affliction, I think you know the rest.
You should be careful. Plenty would take advantage of that.
Come with me. Might as well carry out this hunt together.
You spoke about voices in your head last night. Tell me more.
I would, but you have a lot of hangers-on already. Thin your numbers, then we can talk.
Baldur's Gate is an obvious answer, but we landed too damn far away.
We find a healer - fast. We can't have much time left before ceremorphosis takes hold.
Don't worry about her. I'm the one in charge.
Neither of us agreed to a lot of what's happened lately. Perhaps together, we can change that.
Fair enough. But a leader should always keep potential conflicts in mind, yes?
I can be valuable in more ways than you might expect. When you figure out you need me, just say the word.
There's more to a person than a name. Surely there's more you can tell me.

Synopsis: A follow-up with Shadowheart after her Ultimatum dialogue, where the Box forces her to camp in a haze of murderous madness. Occurs if the player talked her down and got her to rest. She's calmer now, but still unsettled and confused - what is it that compelled her to act against her will like that? She and the player can discuss, but no clear answer emerges. The player can invite her to join their party.
